# .herd/config — read by the herd engine; one per consuming project.
# Shell-sourceable KEY=value. COMMIT this file — it is code-shaped config, not data.
# It must be ZERO-SECRET: API-backend credentials go in .herd/secrets (gitignored), never here.
# `herd init` writes this for you; every key has a generic fallback in herd-config.sh, so only
# set what differs from the defaults.
#
# PER-USER OVERLAY (HERD-47): keep this file for SHARED project policy and put per-user/per-machine
# state (driver binding, model-tier & token-budget choices, operator-posture opt-ins) in a sibling
# .herd/config.local — gitignored, sourced AFTER this file so its keys OVERRIDE the baseline
# (settings.json/settings.local.json convention). Absent ⇒ behavior is identical to this single file.
# Write it via `herd config set --local KEY VALUE` (machine-scoped keys route there automatically);
# `herd config list` shows whether each effective value came from the baseline or the local overlay.
HERD_VERSION=1                       # engine contract version (herd upgrade bumps this)

PROJECT_ROOT="$HOME/source/myproject"          # the main checkout
WORKTREES_DIR="$HOME/source/myproject-trees"   # the worktree pool (sibling, never committed)
DEFAULT_BRANCH="origin/main"                   # branch off / push to this
WORKSPACE_NAME="myproject"                     # herdr workspace label
# BRANCH_TEMPLATE — how the lanes name their feature branches (HERD-120). Default 'feat/{slug}' is
# byte-identical to the historically-hardcoded feat/<slug>. Tokens: {slug} (required) and optional
# {ref} (the tracker id, filled when the coordinator spawns from a tracked item). A malformed
# template (no {slug}) warns and falls back to the default. Uncomment to use a project convention:
# BRANCH_TEMPLATE="feat/{slug}"                # e.g. "{ref}/{slug}" → HERD-120/my-slug · "wip/{slug}"

BACKLOG_FILE="BACKLOG.md"            # repo-relative; the scribe's single shared file
SCRIBE_BACKEND="file"               # work-tracker backend: file (default) | changelog
# SCRIBE_LINGER_SECS — drainer linger window (HERD-88). After the scribe empties the queue, the
# drainer keeps polling this many extra seconds before its session exits, so a burst of backlog
# updates arriving with short idle gaps is drained by ONE scribe session instead of paying a fresh
# MODEL_SCRIBE cold-start per gap. Default 0 → byte-identical to today; 90 is a good burst-sharing value.
# SCRIBE_LINGER_SECS="90"
# DRAINER_HEARTBEAT_TIMEOUT — drainer singleton liveness window in seconds (HERD-109). The scribe and
# researcher drainers are per-project singletons; a same-named drainer already in `herdr agent list`
# makes an enqueue short-circuit. A LISTED but HUNG drainer would then block the queue forever, so the
# *-step.sh drainers heartbeat on every drain step and the enqueue path reclaims the singleton (spawns a
# fresh drainer) when the heartbeat is staler than this. The queue's atomic per-request claim prevents
# double-draining. Default 900 (15 min) → byte-identical to today; set 0 to disable liveness reclaim.
# DRAINER_HEARTBEAT_TIMEOUT="900"
SHARE_LINKS=""                      # gitignored dirs symlinked into each worktree (e.g. "node_modules target")

# BACKLOG_VIEW_EXTRAS — VIEW-ONLY backlog-pane extra section. Default "" (off) → the pane output is
# byte-identical to today. Set "github-issues" and the backlog viewer renders a SECOND, clearly
# labeled '📥 incoming (github issues)' section BENEATH the primary work queue, listing this repo's
# open GitHub issues (the herd-report incoming inbox) via `gh issue list`. Strictly ADDITIVE: never
# merged into the primary list, never feeds `herd backlog` or coordinator work-selection —
# SCRIBE_BACKEND stays the single source of truth for planned work. Fails SOFT on any gh error (a
# quiet 'incoming unavailable' note, never a red row). Takes effect on the backlog pane's next launch
# (herd pane backlog / herd reload).
# BACKLOG_VIEW_EXTRAS=""              # "" (off, default) | github-issues

# TASK_PANE_VIEW — builder-tab task-spec viewer. DEFAULT on: the builder lanes (herd-quick.sh /
# herd-feature.sh) render the builder's live task spec ($WORKTREES_DIR/<slug>.task.md) in the tab's
# OTHERWISE-IDLE root pane via task-spec-view.sh (glow + the bundled tokyonight style, repaint on
# mtime, a quiet dim 'task spec removed' line when the file is reaped — never red), so a human sees
# WHAT the agent was told to build instead of a bare shell. Strictly ADDITIVE UX: the pane is unused
# today, so off restores the bare shell exactly. Launched only when the root pane is not hosting the
# app preview, and never under the headless driver (no panes → clean no-op).
# TASK_PANE_VIEW="on"                 # on (default) | off

# DOCTOR_STARTUP_HINT — PROACTIVE soft-dependency surfacing on control-room startup (herd reload /
# coordinator launch). Default "off": startup prints nothing extra, byte-identical to today. Set "on"
# and startup emits one DIM line per MISSING soft dep (glow -> raw backlog pane, shellcheck -> no lint,
# bats -> direct test run), each naming what it degrades, then a dim pointer to `herd doctor` for the
# install command. Never red, never blocks (soft deps only degrade; the no-false-red rule). So you
# learn what's missing at startup instead of when the degradation bites. Takes effect on the next
# herd reload / coordinator launch.
# DOCTOR_STARTUP_HINT="off"           # off (default) | on

# HERD_THEME — pluggable theming across ALL herd color surfaces (consoles, glow viewers, the CLI).
# Default "tokyonight" (the shipped built-in), byte-identical to the pre-theme hardcoded palettes. A
# theme is a DIRECTORY with two files: palette.sh (console C_* truecolor + optional C_CLI_* 16-color
# CLI overrides) and glow.json (the glamour style). Resolution order, per file: .herd/themes/<name>/
# (your own, project-local) -> templates/themes/<name>/ (engine built-ins) -> tokyonight fallback. An
# unknown or broken theme warns once and falls back — it never breaks a console. Fails soft: a missing
# theme file uses the built-in default, and NO_COLOR or a non-TTY renders plain. To add your own theme:
# copy templates/themes/tokyonight/ to .herd/themes/mytheme/, edit palette.sh + glow.json, set
# HERD_THEME="mytheme". See docs/theming.md.
# HERD_THEME="tokyonight"             # tokyonight (default) | any dir under templates/themes/ or .herd/themes/

# health + preview — the two big project-specific commands.
# `herd init` seeds .herd/healthcheck.project.sh from the template matching scout's detected stack
# (Go → healthcheck.go.sh, Rust → healthcheck.rust.sh, Java → healthcheck.java.sh, Node →
# healthcheck.node.sh, Python/unknown → healthcheck.project.sh); swap the body for your own gate.
HEALTHCHECK_CMD=".herd/healthcheck.project.sh"  # exit 0 clean/data-env, 1 code error, 2 data/env
HEALTHCHECK_HEAVY_GLOB=""            # egrep of diff paths that force the heavy profile; BLANK (default) → every change is heavy. Set a layout-specific value (e.g. "^app/", "^cmd/|^internal/", "^src/") only if some changes can skip the full suite.
APP_SURFACE_GLOB=""                 # optional; egrep of diff paths that are the app surface (e.g. "^app/", "^cmd/", "^src/"); BLANK (default) → interaction gate off
INTERACTION_TEST_CMD=""             # optional; drives an input + asserts the dependent output changed (0 clean/1 code/2 data-env); e.g. a UI test harness that sets a value, re-runs, and asserts the output moved
APP_PREVIEW_CMD=""                  # optional; omit → no preview pane (quick-only project)
SMOKE_CMD=""                        # optional; an extra smoke gate used by the resolver

# app-preview knobs — all optional; the defaults below reproduce today's web-app behavior EXACTLY,
# so leave them unset unless your preview is a non-web-framework command. Consumed by app-monitor.sh
# (launch args + health probe) and the feature/resolver lanes (port range).
#   APP_PREVIEW_SERVER_ARGS: extra args appended to APP_PREVIEW_CMD; {port} is substituted by the
#     chosen port. Set "" for a command that reads $PORT itself and needs no injected flags.
#   APP_PREVIEW_HEALTH_CMD:  health probe command (PORT exported; exit 0 = 🟢 serving). Highest
#     precedence; empty falls through to the HTTP path probe. Set for a CLI / gRPC / non-HTTP preview.
#   APP_PREVIEW_HEALTH_PATH: HTTP path curled at localhost:$PORT<path> (200 = 🟢). Set "" to DISABLE
#     the HTTP probe → health shows ⚪ unknown (never a false-red 🔴) when no health CMD is set either.
#   APP_PREVIEW_PORT_BASE:   base of the lanes' free-port search (base..base+98). Set to your stack's
#     convention (e.g. 8080, 3000).
# APP_PREVIEW_SERVER_ARGS="--server.port {port} --server.headless true"
# APP_PREVIEW_HEALTH_CMD=""
# APP_PREVIEW_HEALTH_PATH="/"
# APP_PREVIEW_PORT_BASE="8501"

# model map — role → model. Eco-leaning STARTER defaults: Opus is now an ESCALATION tier, not a
# default — reach it deterministically via MODEL_ESCALATE_GLOB (feature lane) / REVIEW_ESCALATE_GLOB
# (review gate). An explicit MODEL_* key here ALWAYS beats the starter default (TOKEN_MODE and the
# escalate globs compose on top of whatever you set).
#
# Every MODEL_* value accepts an optionally runtime-qualified ref '<driver>:<model>' (HERD-151): a BARE
# model id (as below) runs on the default driver — byte-identical to before — while a '<driver>:' prefix
# pins that role to a shipped runtime driver (templates/drivers/<name>.driver), e.g.
# MODEL_QUICK="headless:claude-haiku-4-5". An unknown driver prefix FAILS LOUDLY at spawn time (never a
# silent fallback). 'herd config set MODEL_*' suggests from templates/models.tsv (see 'herd config
# models'); an uncatalogued model is allowed with a soft note — your model is never refused.
MODEL_COORDINATOR="claude-opus-4-8"
MODEL_FEATURE="claude-sonnet-4-6"   # eco default; escalate to Opus via MODEL_ESCALATE_GLOB
MODEL_QUICK="claude-haiku-4-5"      # trivial lane → cheapest tier
MODEL_SCRIBE="claude-sonnet-4-6"
MODEL_RESEARCH="claude-sonnet-4-6"
MODEL_REVIEW="claude-sonnet-4-6"    # pre-merge gate; escalate to Opus via REVIEW_ESCALATE_GLOB
# MODEL_ADVISE="claude-opus-4-8"    # `herd advise` one-shot advisor; defaults to the MODEL_FEATURE tier

# docs-only review tier (HERD-89) — route pure-docs diffs to the cheapest reviewer. Leave both blank
# (default) for byte-identical behavior; set DOCS_ONLY_GLOB to opt in. ESCALATION WINS: a docs diff
# also matching REVIEW_ESCALATE_GLOB or over REVIEW_ESCALATE_MAXFILES files stays on the STRONG tier.
# DOCS_ONLY_GLOB='\.(md|txt)$'        # every changed path matches → $REVIEW_MODEL_DOCS review
# REVIEW_MODEL_DOCS="claude-haiku-4-5"  # cheapest tier for pure-docs diffs

# privacy / safety
DENY_PATHS="data/"                  # never committed; the local lane is scoped here
REVIEW_CHECKLIST=".herd/review-checklist.md"  # project risk list injected into the review gate

# the generated coordinator skill the control room launches
COORDINATOR_CMD="/coordinator"

# driver — the runtime-specific control surface (multiplexer + agent runtime) the coordinator skill
# is bound to. Selects templates/drivers/<name>.driver, whose DRIVER_* incantations are substituted
# into the rendered coordinator skill. Two drivers ship:
#   herdr-claude (default) — herdr multiplexer + Claude Code; renders the skill functionally
#     identical to before the driver abstraction (the byte-identical default).
#   headless — NO herdr panes: agents run detached, panes become a VIEW not a dependency, and the
#     watcher / journal / notifications / limit detection run headless (Windows / CI / headless Linux).
# An unknown value fails `herd render` loudly, listing the available drivers.
HERD_DRIVER="herdr-claude"

# merge policy — how the watcher acts after all gates (healthcheck + review) pass.
#   auto    — merge immediately (default).
#   approve — hold and notify; run  herd approve <pr#>  (or herd-approve.sh approve <pr#>)
#             to write an explicit sha-keyed approval. A new commit invalidates prior approval.
#   observe — run gates and report/notify, but NEVER merge automatically.
# Takes precedence over WATCHER_AUTOMERGE when set.
MERGE_POLICY="auto"

# human-verify policy (HERD-59) — how the watcher handles a PR that declares a HUMAN-VERIFY: block
# under MERGE_POLICY=auto. A builder that could not itself run a manual step (a live smoke test, a
# UI/pane check) declares it under a HUMAN-VERIFY: marker in the PR body; today such a PR is ALWAYS
# held for a sha-keyed approval, even under auto. This lever changes that, opt-in only:
#   hold        default — today's EXACT behavior, byte-identical when unset: the PR is held and
#               released by  herd-approve.sh approve <pr#>  after the steps are verified.
#   coordinator keep the hold, but notify loudly and flag it coordinator-actionable — a coordinator/
#               agent executes the declared steps and approves via  herd-approve.sh approve <pr#>.
#   auto        treat the declared steps as INFORMATIONAL: journal them + comment them on the PR, and
#               merge on green gates (the standing human-verify authorization, codified as a switch).
# Unknown/empty falls back to hold. Watcher-affecting: takes effect on the next watcher restart.
# HUMAN_VERIFY_POLICY="hold"   # hold (default) | coordinator | auto

# merge method — the gh pr merge strategy applied by do_merge (default: merge commit).
MERGE_METHOD="merge"    # merge | squash | rebase

# gate dispatch (HERD-73) — WHEN the watcher fires the pre-merge review relative to the healthcheck.
#   serial   default — byte-identical to today: the review dispatches only AFTER the healthcheck
#            outcome lands, so gate wall-clock = health + review.
#   parallel dispatch the review at the same tick the healthcheck STARTS, so the two gates overlap
#            (wall-clock ≈ max(health, review)). The MERGE decision is UNCHANGED — a merge still
#            requires BOTH gates green; REVIEW_CONCURRENCY + the sha-keyed review-once semantics are
#            respected, and a health code-error mid-review never kills the reviewer. Tradeoff: a
#            health-failed sha wastes one review run (cheap under REVIEW_ESCALATE_GLOB tiering).
# Opt-in only; watcher-affecting (takes effect on the next watcher restart).
# GATE_DISPATCH="serial"   # serial (default) | parallel

# native-burst (HERD-107) — the bounded read-only FAN-OUT seam (scripts/herd/burst.sh).
#   off  default — byte-identical to today: research fan-out is un-hinted; the review is a single reviewer.
#   on   read-only work may BURST — fan out several CONCURRENT calls bounded by REVIEW_CONCURRENCY (the
#        ceiling): research.sh hints the drainer a bounded concurrent-Explore width, and herd-review.sh
#        may run a bounded REVIEW PANEL (see REVIEW_PANEL). WRITE lanes (scribe/backlog/merge) NEVER
#        burst — they stay strictly serial. Additive + opt-in; unknown/blank → off (fail safe).
# NATIVE_BURST="off"       # off (default) | on
# review panel size — CONCURRENT read-only reviewer passes over the SAME diff when NATIVE_BURST=on;
# effective size is min(REVIEW_PANEL, REVIEW_CONCURRENCY). Default 1 = single reviewer (byte-identical).
# Combination is fail-safe: ANY member's BLOCK blocks the merge; a merge needs >=1 PASS and zero BLOCKs.
# REVIEW_PANEL="1"         # concurrent reviewer passes when NATIVE_BURST=on (default 1)

# post-merge main-health tick (HERD-129) — catch a RED default branch AT MERGE TIME. The pre-merge
# health gate proves each PR green in ISOLATION, but two independently-green PRs can merge into a
# broken COMBINATION (a real incident left main red ~2h, found only when later unrelated PRs inherited
# it). ON → after every merge the watcher runs the healthcheck against the freshly ff'd default-branch
# HEAD (sha-keyed so each main sha runs once; runs the FULL heavy suite — a light check against the
# default-branch checkout is a zero-file vacuous green; honors HEALTH_CONCURRENCY) and, on a
# reproduced red, raises a LOUD persistent 'MAIN RED — <failing
# test> (since #N)' console row + a notification, cleared when a later sha goes green. An ALARM only —
# never a merge gate, revert, or re-merge; fully fail-soft. Ships OFF (byte-inert: no suite, no row).
# MAIN_HEALTH_TICK="off"   # off (default) | on

# Watcher-console FLAIR pack (HERD-147) — an ADDITIVE cosmetic layer on the live 'herd watch' console.
# ON → (a) a merge CELEBRATION: the status tick after a merge prints one theme-colored line
# '🐑 #<pr> joins the flock · <n> grazing'; (b) a PASTURE HEADER: one line rendering the in-flight herd
# by state — 🐑 grazing (building), 💤 idle, ✅ in the pen (done). Colors come only from the active
# theme (theme.sh C_* vars); NO_COLOR / non-tty renders plain. HARD RULE: flair NEVER softens a
# red/dead/needs-you state — a 💀 dead or ⚠️ needs-you builder is exactly as loud as today, and it never
# touches a gate or a merge decision. Ships OFF (byte-inert: every console byte identical to before).
# WATCHER_FLAIR="off"      # off (default) | on

# Cross-seat OPERATOR INBOX (HERD-184) — so coordination messages left as comments reach an autonomous
# coordinator automatically. ON → each watcher tick surfaces NEW comments by OTHER authors as a
# 'operator inbox' console section (needs-you-adjacent) plus one notify-once per comment: (a) a
# PR-COMMENT feed — new comments on the open PRs this seat authored or is gating (e.g. a "don't
# self-merge, main broke" left on a PR); (b) a TRACKER feed — new comments by other operators on items
# this seat claimed/marked, read via the active SCRIBE_BACKEND's optional comment reader (linear).
# ADDITIVE + FAIL-SOFT: a missing reader / api error / no credentials = empty inbox, NEVER a red row;
# it never touches a gate or a merge decision. Ships OFF (byte-inert: no reader runs, console identical).
# OPERATOR_INBOX="off"     # off (default) | on

# INFRA-timeout circuit breaker (HERD-110) — stop the watcher re-dispatching gates into a dead/hung
# environment. It tracks CONSECUTIVE INFRA failures (non-verdict reviewer deaths — a claude exec-hang,
# an env failure, a reviewer that dies WITHOUT writing a verdict), GLOBALLY across all PRs. After
# INFRA_BREAKER_MAX in a row the breaker OPENS: new review/health dispatch stops, a loud
# 'infra circuit open — environment looks dead' status row + journal event surface, and after
# INFRA_BREAKER_COOLDOWN seconds it goes HALF-OPEN for a SINGLE probe (a real verdict closes it, another
# death re-opens it). CRITICAL: a real code BLOCK/PASS verdict proves the env is alive and RESETS the
# counter — it never trips the breaker; only non-verdict deaths do. Ships OFF (byte-inert): default 0.
# INFRA_BREAKER_MAX="0"          # 0 (default, off) | N>=1 = open after N consecutive INFRA (non-verdict) failures
# INFRA_BREAKER_COOLDOWN="300"   # seconds OPEN before a single half-open probe retry (non-numeric → 300)

# Claude exec-hang probe (HERD-108) — detect a WEDGED claude up front instead of feeding dead
# dispatches. On some environments `claude` hangs on invocation (every exec stalls before the process
# finishes starting — e.g. the macOS com.apple.quarantine _dyld_start hang); a wedged claude makes every
# review/refix spawn a corpse and the poll loop burns cycles against a hang it cannot see. When armed,
# the watcher probes `claude --version` under a HARD timeout ONCE per tick before dispatching; a timeout
# HOLDS that tick's review/refix with a loud 'claude exec-hang' row + a journal infra_event (run
# `herd doctor` — its own `claude responds` check reports the same hang with a fix). Only a genuine
# timeout counts as a hang; a broken/absent claude is fail-soft and never holds the queue. Ships OFF
# (byte-inert): default 0 → no probe exec, no journal, behavior byte-identical.
# WATCH_CLAUDE_PROBE_TIMEOUT="0"  # 0 (default, off) | N>=1 = `claude --version` probe timeout in seconds

# PR flow — how builders open PRs. SAFE DEFAULTS (direct + builder) preserve today's exact behavior:
# a plain `gh pr create`. Only the LANE RULES text (herd-quick.sh / herd-feature.sh) reads these.
#   PR_FLOW:       direct — open PRs ready to merge (default, today's behavior).
#                  draft  — builder opens `gh pr create --draft`; the watcher already holds DRAFT
#                           PRs until they are marked ready.
#   PR_READY_WHEN: who promotes a DRAFT to ready — builder (self, once the healthcheck passes) |
#                  coordinator | human. Only consulted when PR_FLOW=draft.
PR_FLOW="direct"          # direct | draft
PR_READY_WHEN="builder"   # builder | coordinator | human   (only used when PR_FLOW=draft)

# PUSH_GATE (HERD-123) — gate-then-upload: hold a FINISHED builder for human review BEFORE anything
# reaches GitHub. The missing seam: PR_FLOW=draft gates AFTER the push (PR already public);
# MERGE_POLICY=approve gates AFTER review (PR exists); PUSH_GATE=human gates BEFORE the push, while the
# diff is still only local. With =human the builder completes work + healthcheck but STOPS before
# `git push` / `gh pr create`, recording a sha-keyed hold the watcher shows as 'ready · awaiting push
# approval' with the worktree path; a human reviews the LOCAL diff and runs `herd-approve.sh approve
# <slug>`, which resumes the push + PR creation. A new commit after the hold invalidates a prior
# approval. SAFE DEFAULT: '' (off) → lanes byte-identical, this gate never fires.
PUSH_GATE=""              # "" (default, off) | human

# delete the head branch after a merge. false (default) preserves today's behavior (branches kept).
DELETE_BRANCH_ON_MERGE="false"   # true | false

# pre-PR local review mode: none (default) | pre-pr | risk-scoped. pre-pr makes every builder pass a
# local adversarial correctness review (herd-review.sh --local) BEFORE opening its PR. risk-scoped
# runs that review ONLY when the builder's diff surface matches LOCAL_REVIEW_GLOB below — low-risk
# diffs skip straight to the PR (the watcher's post-PR review gate stays authoritative), so review
# quota is spent only where round-1 BLOCKs cluster. Either way the post-PR gate is unchanged.
LOCAL_REVIEW="none"       # none | pre-pr | risk-scoped
# Egrep pattern of changed-file paths (git diff DEFAULT_BRANCH...HEAD --name-only) that make a
# LOCAL_REVIEW=risk-scoped builder run the pre-PR local review; a diff touching no matching path skips
# it. Same egrep semantics as REVIEW_ESCALATE_GLOB / HEALTHCHECK_HEAVY_GLOB; a DEDICATED key so the
# pre-PR risk surface is scoped independently of the post-PR review tiering. Blank (default) → with
# risk-scoped it fails SOFT to unconditional pre-pr (loud warn); ignored under none/pre-pr.
LOCAL_REVIEW_GLOB=""      # e.g. '^scripts/herd/|^bin/'  — engine paths where pre-PR review pays off

# builder context provisioning (HERD-40) — a SPACE-SEPARATED list of grounding sources injected into
# the STABLE preamble of every spawned builder's task spec, so builders start grounded instead of
# re-exploring the repo each session. EMPTY (default) → nothing injected, task specs byte-identical to
# today. First source: `codemap` → injects a pointer to the deterministic engine-tree map committed at
# docs/codemap.md (run `herd codemap` to generate it) so the builder reads the map first. Extensible:
# future sources plug in as new tokens; an unknown token is ignored. Injected grounding stays in the
# prompt-cache-shared STABLE prefix, never interleaved with per-task text.
CONTEXT_PROVISION=""      # e.g. "codemap"  (space-separate multiple sources)

# builder MCP tool provisioning (HERD-41) — the TOOLS sibling of CONTEXT_PROVISION. A SPACE-SEPARATED
# list of MCP server names wired into every spawned builder worktree's project-level
# .claude/settings.json (its mcpServers block), so a builder can use those tools with no per-session
# setup. EMPTY (default) → nothing written, settings.json byte-identical to today. The write is
# ADDITIVE + NON-CLOBBER (an existing/user-authored server of the same name is never overwritten),
# idempotent, and atomic — the same guarantees as the rate-limit hook it merges alongside.
# Each name resolves to a {command,args,env} entry from a BUILT-IN default, overridable per server via
#   MCP_<NAME>_COMMAND / MCP_<NAME>_ARGS / MCP_<NAME>_ENV
# (NAME = the server name upper-cased with -/. → _; e.g. context7 → MCP_CONTEXT7_*). These per-server
# keys are DYNAMIC (not registered for `herd config set`) — set them by editing THIS file directly. A
# name with no built-in and no _COMMAND override is ignored (forward-compatible), never an error.
# PRIVACY — credentials are NEVER written here or into the generated settings.json. MCP_<NAME>_ENV is a
# space-separated list of env-var NAMES to pass through; only the reference string "${VAR}" is written,
# and Claude Code expands it at launch from the runtime environment (populated from .herd/secrets).
# Put the actual secret in .herd/secrets (gitignored), never in this committed file.
# Built-in examples:
#   context7      — up-to-date library docs (npx -y @upstash/context7-mcp; passes CONTEXT7_API_KEY
#                   through). Valuable on real code CONSUMER projects herdkit runs on; low-value in
#                   bash herdkit itself — the MECHANISM is the deliverable.
#   graphify-mcp  — a LOCAL example server (the `graphify` codemap tool's MCP surface, if installed).
# Example (uncomment to wire context7, with the API key living in .herd/secrets):
#   MCP_PROVISION="context7"
#   # MCP_CONTEXT7_ARGS="-y @upstash/context7-mcp@latest"   # override the built-in args if needed
MCP_PROVISION=""          # e.g. "context7"  (space-separate multiple servers)

# coordinator-side graphify (HERD-61) — the THIRD LEG of the graphify integration, sibling to the two
# builder-side keys above: CONTEXT_PROVISION=codemap grounds each BUILDER in docs/codemap.md, and
# MCP_PROVISION graphify-mcp gives a BUILDER the graphify MCP tools; this key gives the COORDINATOR a
# pre-spawn/periodic overlap read. graphify is machine-local (PyPI `graphifyy`, usually at
# ~/.local/bin/graphify). Point this at the binary on THIS machine so the coordinator can rebuild
# graphify-out/graph.json LLM-free (`graphify update --no-cluster`, zero Claude quota) and cross the
# changed-file surfaces of in-flight worktrees before spawning a colliding item.
#   • MACHINE-scoped (HERD-47): the path is per-machine — set it with `herd config set GRAPHIFY_BIN
#     <path>`, which routes to the gitignored .herd/config.local, NOT this committed baseline.
#   • FAIL-SOFT: unset falls back to `graphify` on PATH; if neither resolves, the coordinator SKIPS the
#     analysis SILENTLY (no warning, no red row) — it is an optional accelerator, never required.
#   • HONEST SCOPE: FILE-level overlap + within-file structure only — graphify's bash cross-file CALL
#     resolution is weak, so this is not a cross-script call graph (see the skill for the detail).
# Example (per-machine, in .herd/config.local — not here):
#   GRAPHIFY_BIN="$HOME/.local/bin/graphify"

# legacy back-compat lever — still read when MERGE_POLICY is unset/empty.
#   true  → equivalent to MERGE_POLICY=auto    (merge automatically)
#   false → equivalent to MERGE_POLICY=approve (hold for explicit human approval)
# Prefer MERGE_POLICY for new projects; WATCHER_AUTOMERGE is kept for back-compat only.
WATCHER_AUTOMERGE="true"

# team mode — multi-user auto-merge ownership gate (agent-watch.sh). Both optional; the defaults
# below preserve today's exact SOLO behavior, so leave them unset for a single-operator install.
#   WATCHER_SCOPE:  mine (default) — auto-merge the operator's own PRs, byte-identical to today's solo
#     watcher (the ownership probe stays dormant) | all — team mode: teammates' PRs are DISPLAYED but
#     auto-merge is STRICTLY scoped to WATCHER_OWNER's PRs (a teammate's PR shows "not mine — manual"
#     and is never auto-merged, even when MERGEABLE+CLEAN+approved). A NARROWING gate layered on the
#     watcher lens: it can only ever WITHHOLD a merge, never authorize one the gates would deny.
#   WATCHER_OWNER:  operator GitHub login that owns auto-merge when WATCHER_SCOPE=all. Resolution
#     order: WATCHER_OWNER → WATCHER_VIEW_AUTHOR → `gh api user`. Fail-closed: if it cannot resolve
#     in team mode, auto-merge is WITHHELD for safety (a teammate's PR is never blind-merged).
# WATCHER_SCOPE="mine"
# WATCHER_OWNER=""

# tracker-routed spawn enforcement (HERD-64) — make "every builder is traceable to a tracked work
# item" a PROJECT POLICY, not just a coordinator convention. DEFAULT off: the spawn surfaces
# (herd-quick.sh / herd-feature.sh / spawn.sh) impose no gate, byte-identical to today.
#   required → a spawn carrying NO tracker ref (HERD_CLAIM_ID, else the HERD_ITEM_REF the coordinator
#              threads for a tracked item) is REFUSED with a loud one-line reason and creates nothing.
#              HERD_FORCE_SPAWN=1 (or a lane's --force) is the explicit escape hatch — it lets the
#              spawn through and JOURNALS the bypass (visible in `herd log`).
# Composes with CLAIM_REQUIRED (HERD-50): the ref set is identical, so with BOTH on every spawn is
# atomically CLAIMED (no double-build) AND visible in the tracker. TRACKED_SPAWNS enforces VISIBILITY,
# CLAIM_REQUIRED enforces EXCLUSIVITY. Recommended for shared / multi-operator repos.
# TRACKED_SPAWNS="off"   # off (default) | required

# routing — where engine bugs escalate (herd report files a gh issue here)
HERD_REPO="briankeegan1/herdkit"

# dep-watcher poll cadence + stall surfacing (dep-watcher.sh). All optional; the defaults below
# preserve today's behavior, so leave them unset unless you want to retune.
#   DEP_POLL_MIN:  initial poll interval (seconds); also the value a state change resets backoff to.
#   DEP_POLL_MAX:  max poll interval (seconds) after capped-exponential backoff while deps sit idle.
#   DEP_STALE_TTL: seconds a still-open dep may go without upstream movement before it is surfaced
#                  as `stalled` (loudly, but still polled — never a freeze); 0 disables stall surfacing.
# DEP_POLL_MIN="30"
# DEP_POLL_MAX="300"
# DEP_STALE_TTL="86400"

# coordinator watchdog — opt-in coordinator auto-resume (agent-watch.sh). DEFAULT off: with it unset
# or off the watcher never touches the coordinator, byte-identical to today. Builders already get a
# rate_limit hook + auto-resume; the coordinator (coordinator.sh → `claude … /coordinator`, running
# from the main checkout) does not — so if it hits the account usage limit unattended it parks at
# Claude's interactive menu and ALL orchestration halts until a human resumes it. Set to on and this
# watcher revives it the same way it revives a builder: at the reset (+HERD_LIMIT_RESUME_BUFFER) it
# relaunches the coordinator in place via `claude --continue` in the coordinator pane. Safety rails:
# it acts ONLY on a CONFIRMED park (a limit sentinel/banner AND the coordinator agent is not
# 'working'), never relaunches a healthy/working coordinator, takes a WORKSPACE_NAME-keyed launch
# lock so it never double-launches, and escalates a failed resume via notification without looping.
# ACTIVATION is a deliberate two-part operator step: set COORDINATOR_WATCHDOG=on AND restart the
# watcher (this flag is read at watcher launch). Recommended for unattended/overnight runs.
# COORDINATOR_WATCHDOG="off"   # off (default) | on

# dead-builder AUTO-RESPAWN — opt-in restart of a silently-dead pre-PR builder (agent-watch.sh).
# DEFAULT off: with it unset or off the watcher only DETECTS + surfaces a dead builder (a 💀 row +
# one notification), byte-identical to today. A dead builder is one whose agent has VANISHED from
# `herdr agent list` while its worktree still exists and it opened NO PR — nothing revives it, so an
# empty worktree strands until a human notices. Set to on and the watcher also RESTARTS it, surgically
# and once: it starts a FRESH agent in the EXISTING worktree pointed at the same
# $WORKTREES_DIR/<slug>.task.md (it reuses the spawn pattern, NOT the full lane — no new
# worktree/branch, no app-preview pane). Two hard safety rails: it respawns ONLY when the worktree has
# NO commits ahead of base AND no staged/unstaged/untracked changes (it never blows away work — a dead
# builder that produced anything escalates via notification instead), and AT MOST ONCE per slug (a
# slug-keyed ledger; a builder that dies AGAIN after its one respawn escalates and is never respawned
# a second time, so it can never loop). Recommended for unattended/overnight runs.
# DEAD_BUILDER_AUTORESPAWN="off"   # off (default) | on
